The Crags Resort presents an exceptional opportunity for the right operator to revitalize this historic early-1900s property, offering breathtaking views of Estes Park. Perched above the town at the edge of the mountains, the resort is surrounded by the granite peaks of Rocky Mountain National Park. With vistas overlooking the iconic Stanley Hotel, Lake Estes, and downtown Estes Park just a short walk away, the setting is truly unparalleled. As one of the nation’s premier wedding destinations, Estes Park positions The Crags Resort as an ideal opportunity for a developer to create one of the most desirable venues in the region. Originally built in 1910, the resort features: 27 guest rooms, a spacious, open dining room, warm and inviting stone fireplaces. This historic charm makes it a perfect setting for corporate retreats from Denver, family reunions, and weddings—offering unforgettable experiences in one of America’s most iconic national parks. Since the early 1980s, the resort has operated as a timeshare. Now, these rooms represent fresh inventory in a supply-constrained market and are ready to welcome guests. Additionally, the recent conversion of Fall River Village into affordable housing has created an upper-upscale market gap—one that The Crags Resort is uniquely positioned to fill, especially for events and group sales. Sitting on over four acres, the property offers multiple opportunities for expansion, such as: Additional guest rooms, event spaces, or parking to enhance operational value, an expanded deck for the bar, maximizing the spectacular views, a poolside pavilion or covered event space to extend the wedding and event season. The Annex Building: Currently facing structural challenges, this building could be redeveloped into a two- or three-story structure with added guest rooms and/or covered parking. Upper Parcel: Presently used for parking, this site could be reimagined to include covered parking, more guest accommodations, or event space. With the right vision and design approach, the Town of Estes Park has been supportive of developers who appreciate the area’s distinctive character. This is a rare opportunity to breathe new life into a historic property while capitalizing on Estes Park’s thriving tourism and event-driven economy.

A four story infill structure near the central business district of downtown Santa Monica, this project looked to explore both the aesthetic and physical relationships posed by the intersection of concrete and steel building materials. Sculpted forms and elements combined with a simple yet unique organizational ‘bridge-driven’ scheme to respond to the mild beach-side climate. Two floors of office space sit above two floors of parking (one subterranean). Circulation is isolated and pulled away from the south face in order to maximize the light and view potential via a continuous storefront system. A translucent ‘Kalwall’ vault spans the upper footprint of the building to emit a consistent, filtered light throughout the day. A cast-in-place concrete frame becomes a ‘brei-soleil’ that fronts the street and shades east & west facing glazing. A steel shear frame, highlighted in yellow, provides a distinct character and scale for the exposed circulation components. Cross ventilation vents allow seaside breezes to flow through the office spaces. A sculpted concrete fountain introduces a continuous sound element that masks some of the street noise below.
